Interestingly, the directed collective migration into the free space requires that the motile force generated by a polarised cell (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${F}_{{\rm{\max }}}$$\end{document}Fmax) is sufficiently strong. Otherwise either the polarisation cannot propagate backward into the bulk or the cell layer cannot expand. In either case the migration stops after a short transient period. The minimal value of the motile force required for the propagation of the polarisation wave into the bulk and for sustained directed migration increases with the cortical contractility of the cells; see Fig. 5(b).

