Our model also indicates that the cells cortex contractility plays an essential role in regulating the formation of the swirling movement, i.e. the swirls are more likely to form when the cortex contractility is weak; see Fig. 4(a,b). This is explained using Eqs. (1–4). Cells with a weak cortex contractility (e.g., \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\lambda }_{{\rm{cont}}}=0.3$$\end{document}λcont=0.3) can more easily change their shape which can also lead to the displacement of the center of mass of the cells. This displacement can spontaneously polarise the cell, due to the bistable behaviour of the cell polarity \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$|{\overrightarrow{p}}_{\sigma }|$$\end{document}|p→σ|; see Fig. 1(a). The spontaneous cell polarisation becomes more likely when the polarisation threshold \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha $$\end{document}α is lower. This resembles the experimental observations showing that the intensity of the polarisation promotes the appearance of the swirls58. Then, the motile force \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\overrightarrow{F}}_{\sigma }$$\end{document}F→σ generated by a spontaneous polarisation is transmitted to the neighbouring cells leading to the formation of swirling movements. This suggests that sufficiently strengthening the cells cortical contractility would increase the overall alignment of the migration by transforming the swirling movements into a directed cell sheet migration; see Fig. 4(a,b).

On the other hand, excessive strengthening of the cells cortex contractility can block the collective migration in a monolayer; see Fig. 5(b) and Movie 5. A tight cortical contractility results in symmetric hexagon-like cell shapes corresponding to the “hard” regime (Fig. 2) that blocks the cells polarisation by limiting their deformation and motility. The “hard” cell shapes can only have relatively little displacement of the center of mass, corresponding to weak cell polarity and motile force. This blockage of the active motility can also be caused by increasing the decay rate of the cell polarisation \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta $$\end{document}β. At high \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta $$\end{document}β, the cells do not possess non-zero steady-state for the polarity and their polarity magnitude can only stabilise at zero; see Fig. 1(a) and our discussion in35. Then, starting with an initial polarity, the cells gradually loose their polarity and stop moving. Therefore, the polarisation wave becomes unstable and disappears gradually after the barrier is lifted; see Movie 6.
